H2 Database vs MySQL 

PART 1: What is H2 & How it Worked in Our Project

What is H2 Database?
H2 is an IN-MEMORY database
"In-Memory" means → data lives inside RAM (not saved to disk)
When your Spring Boot app STARTS → database is created
When your Spring Boot app STOPS → database is GONE (deleted)

It's like a whiteboard:
✅ Easy to write on
✅ No setup needed
❌ When you erase (stop app) → everything gone

How H2 Worked Automatically in Our Project
When you ran the app, look at your console logs — everything happened automatically:
Step 1:
HikariPool-1 - Added connection conn0: url=jdbc:h2:mem:testdb
→ H2 created a database called "testdb" inside RAM

Step 2:
Hibernate: drop table if exists users cascade
→ Spring deleted old table if it existed (fresh start)

Step 3:
Hibernate: create table users (id bigint, email varchar, name varchar)
→ Spring READ your User.java class
→ Automatically created the "users" table for you!
→ You never wrote any SQL yourself!

Step 4:
Tomcat started on port 8080
→ Server ready, H2 database ready, everything connected!
Why it worked with ZERO setup:
You added H2 dependency in pom.xml
         ↓
Spring Boot saw H2 in dependencies
         ↓
Spring Boot auto-configured everything
         ↓
No username, no password, no installation needed!

H2 Console (You Can See the Database Visually!)
Open browser → go to:
http://localhost:8080/h2-console
Fill in:
Driver Class  : org.h2.Driver
JDBC URL      : jdbc:h2:mem:testdb
Username      : sa
Password      : (leave empty)
Click Connect → you can see your users table visually! ✅

H2 Summary
✅ No installation needed
✅ Auto setup by Spring Boot
✅ Great for learning & testing
❌ Data lost when app stops
❌ Cannot use in real production apps


PART 2: How to Switch to MySQL

Step 1: Install MySQL
Download from:
https://dev.mysql.com/downloads/installer/

Download MySQL Installer
During install → choose MySQL Server + MySQL Workbench
Set a root password (remember this! e.g. root123)


Step 2: Create Database in MySQL
Open MySQL Workbench or MySQL Command Line and type:
sqlCREATE DATABASE restapi_db;
That's it — just create the empty database, Spring will create tables automatically!

Step 3: Change pom.xml — Remove H2, Add MySQL
Open pom.xml and make these changes:
Remove H2:
xml<!-- REMOVE THIS -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>
    <artifactId>h2</artifactId>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>
Add MySQL:
xml<!-- ADD THIS -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.mysql</groupId>
    <artifactId>mysql-connector-j</artifactId>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>

Step 4: Change application.properties
Currently your H2 config:
properties# OLD H2 CONFIG — REMOVE ALL THIS
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:h2:mem:testdb
spring.datasource.driver-class-name=org.h2.Driver
spring.datasource.username=sa
spring.datasource.password=
spring.jpa.database-platform=org.hibernate.dialect.H2Dialect
spring.h2.console.enabled=true
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
Replace with MySQL config:
properties# NEW MYSQL CONFIG
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/restapi_db
spring.datasource.driver-class-name=com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver
spring.datasource.username=root
spring.datasource.password=root123
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.dialect=org.hibernate.dialect.MySQLDialect

What Each Line Means:
jdbc:mysql://         → use MySQL driver
localhost             → MySQL is on your own computer
3306                  → MySQL default port number
restapi_db            → database name you created

username=root         → MySQL username
password=root123      → your MySQL password (what you set during install)

ddl-auto=update       → Spring auto creates/updates tables
                        never deletes your data!

show-sql=true         → prints SQL in console so you can see

Step 5: Run the Project
Right click RestApisApplication.java → Run As → Spring Boot App
Console will show:
✅ HikariPool-1 - Added connection → MySQL connected!
✅ Hibernate: create table users (...)  ← if first time
✅ Tomcat started on port 8080

Step 6: Test Same in Postman
Everything stays EXACTLY the same in Postman!
POST http://localhost:8080/users  → creates user
GET  http://localhost:8080/users  → fetch users
PUT  http://localhost:8080/users/1 → update
DELETE http://localhost:8080/users/1 → delete
But now → data is saved permanently in MySQL!
Even after stopping app → data stays! ✅

